25|$|Dean {{was criticized}} during his 2004 presidential {{campaign}} for another decision related to civil unions. Shortly before leaving office, {{he had some}} of his Vermont papers sealed {{for at least the}} next decade, a time frame longer than most outgoing governors use, stating that he was protecting the privacy of many gay supporters who sent him personal letters about the issue. On the campaign trail, he demanded that Vice President Dick Cheney release his <b>energy</b> <b>committee</b> papers. Many people, including Democratic Senator and failed 2004 presidential candidate Joe Lieberman of Connecticut, who left the party after losing his primary for re-election in 2006, accused Dean of hypocrisy. Judicial Watch filed a lawsuit to force the papers be opened before the seal expired, but lost.|$|E
